# ğŸ“Œ 1ï¸âƒ£ Main Types of Loops in JavaScript

1. `for`
2. `while`
3. `do...while`
4. `for...of`
5. `for...in`
6. `forEach()` (array method, not technically a loop)

---

# ğŸ” 1. `for` Loop (Most Flexible)

```js
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  console.log(i);
}
```

Structure:

```js
for (initialization; condition; update)
```

ğŸ§  Mental Model:

* Start
* Check
* Run
* Update
* Repeat

---

## ğŸ”¥ Pro Tips

### 1ï¸âƒ£ You can omit parts

```js
let i = 0;
for (; i < 5;) {
  console.log(i);
  i++;
}
```

### 2ï¸âƒ£ Infinite Loop

```js
for (;;) {
  console.log("Infinite");
}
```

---

# ğŸ”„ 2. `while` Loop

Used when you don't know exact iteration count.

```js
let i = 0;

while (i < 5) {
  console.log(i);
  i++;
}
```

âš  Common Mistake:
Forgetting increment â†’ infinite loop.

---

# ğŸ” 3. `do...while`

Runs at least once.

```js
let i = 0;

do {
  console.log(i);
  i++;
} while (i < 5);
```

ğŸ§  Use when:
You need the loop body to execute at least once.

---

# ğŸ“¦ 4. `for...of` (Modern & Powerful)

Used for iterables:

* Arrays
* Strings
* Maps
* Sets

```js
const arr = [10, 20, 30];

for (const value of arr) {
  console.log(value);
}
```

ğŸ”¥ Cleaner than traditional `for` for arrays.

---

# ğŸ—‚ 5. `for...in` (Object Keys)

Used for object properties:

```js
const user = { name: "Ali", age: 25 };

for (const key in user) {
  console.log(key);        // name, age
  console.log(user[key]);  // Ali, 25
}
```

âš  Do NOT use `for...in` for arrays (bad practice).

---

# ğŸ§  6. `forEach()` (Array Method)

```js
arr.forEach((value, index) => {
  console.log(value);
});
```

âš  Important:
You cannot break or continue inside `forEach`.

This will NOT work:

```js
arr.forEach(v => {
  if (v === 2) break; // âŒ Error
});
```

Use `for...of` instead if you need control.

---

# ğŸ”¥ Break & Continue

## Break

Stops the loop completely.

```js
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  if (i === 3) break;
  console.log(i);
}
```

---

## Continue

Skips current iteration.

```js
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  if (i === 2) continue;
  console.log(i);
}
```

---

# ğŸ§  Scope Trick (Interview Favorite)

```js
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 1000);
}
```

Output:

```
3
3
3
```

Because `var` is function-scoped.

Correct version:

```js
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 1000);
}
```

Output:

```
0
1
2
```

ğŸ”¥ Very common interview question.

---

# âš¡ Performance Tip

Traditional `for` loop is slightly faster than `forEach`, but:

In modern apps â†’ readability > micro-optimization.

---

# ğŸ¯ When to Use What (Real Developer Guide)

| Situation              | Best Choice |
| ---------------------- | ----------- |
| Need index             | `for`       |
| Simple array iteration | `for...of`  |
| Object keys            | `for...in`  |
| Functional style       | `forEach`   |
| Unknown iterations     | `while`     |

---

# ğŸ”¥ Advanced: Labeled Loops

Rare but useful.

```js
outer:
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
    break outer;
  }
}
```

Breaks outer loop.

Used in complex nested loops.

---

# ğŸ§  Infinite Loop Patterns

```js
while (true) {
  // must break manually
}
```

Used in servers, games, polling logic.

---

# ğŸ›‘ Common Mistakes

âŒ Using `for...in` for arrays
âŒ Forgetting `let` in loops
âŒ Infinite loops
âŒ Using `forEach` when you need break
âŒ Modifying array while looping (can cause bugs)

---

# ğŸ”¥ Advanced Loop Trick (Interview)

Reverse Loop (Safe removal pattern):

```js
for (let i = arr.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
  if (arr[i] === 2) {
    arr.splice(i, 1);
  }
}
```

Why reverse?
Because removing shifts indexes.

---

# ğŸ¯ Interview Rapid Summary

* `for` â†’ most flexible
* `while` â†’ condition-based
* `do...while` â†’ runs once minimum
* `for...of` â†’ iterable values
* `for...in` â†’ object keys
* `forEach` â†’ no break/continue
* Use `let` in loops
* Avoid mutating arrays while iterating

